The original salmon population in the Thames became extinct in the 1830s. The Rehabilitation Scheme began in 1979, using fish donated by the fish farming industry and adults returning from these as broodstock. This changed in the mid 1990s and the salmon stocked into the Thames were a mixture of fish from line-bred hatcheries on the  Shannon and Delphi in Ireland.  These were either stocked as fry or smolts. All salmon stocking into the Thames catchment ceased in 2011.
Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Fishpasses were constructed on the Thames weirs to assist salmon migration.  These were mostly Denil, although a few were Larinier.  The weirs at Molesey and Sunbury also had traps so salmon could be tagged and tracked up the river.  The River Kennet also benefited from fishpasses.  These were also a mixture of Denil and Larinier fishpasses.  The TWUL water intakes have had screening added to stop the impingement of fish including migrating salmon smolts. The Thames Tideway Tunnel should improve water quality through the tidal river in summer.
Special Designations: Recovering Salmon River. The River Kennet is designated SSSI. Salmon were introduced into the River Lambourn, which is a tributary of the Kennet and is designated a SAC.
Specific Threats: Weirs associated with navigation on the Thames causing fish passage issues.  Water quantity is an issue in the summer months because of very large abstractions for potable supply. Water quality affects fish populations, both from discharges and river temperature in summer months. Poor water quality through tideway during/after heavy rain due to CSO's.  Because the Thames is a navigation the distance to suitable spawning habitat is confined to tributaries of the Thames.  The most suitable was deemed to be the River Kennet and this is over 50 miles from the tideway.  The Thames has a number of large abstractions which can impact on flows in the Thames and therefore salmon migration both as juveniles leaving the river and adults returning and moving up river.

Significant Recovery and / or Management Actions: Ensure safe passage past (not through) artificial lake near outlet of river. Change operational schedule of sluice between fjord and open sea in order to reduce mortality of both smolt and adult salmon. Removal of remaining migrational obstacles. Reduce avian predation (cormorants) during parr and smolt stage. Continued need for restriction of recreational catches (harvest) of spawners. There is a sluice system with gates that prevent the natural migration of fish between the sea and the river. These gates are closed most of the time, thus hindering the free movement of fish and delaying them in their natural migratory behavior. As a result, there is an artificially high predation due to their prolonged stay at the sluice
Special Designations: Habitats Directive species - protected
Specific Threats: Elevated mortality during passage of artificial lake, where dyke has been damaged, results in major part of river passes through this lake, instead of around this. There is presently an urgent need for this because it will inevitably result in heavy losses of smolt. Also adult migration will likely be delayed. Point mortality at sluice between fjord (where the river has its outlet) and open sea has been found to be very high (bird and seal), partly due to sluice operation timing impeeding/delaying migration. Significant mortality from especially cormorant predation on both parr and smolt.  Migrational obstactes still prevents/delays access to parts of the river system.
